<br>
Raids are one of the ultimate expressions of pack unity. Nothing is more exhilarating than running over the hills, across the plains or down a musty dungeon corridor with packmates.<br>
<br>
However, even this exciting moment can be shattered by poor planning <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I always enjoyed leading raids in Ultima Online and Meridian 59. I've only led small, one group raids in EQ, but I've taken some time to study the aspect of the raid in EQ. Strangely enough, many of the suggestions made by experienced raid leaders hold true through out many online games. <br>
<br>
Here are some suggested guidelines for setting up a pack hunt:<br>
<br>
- Choose a hunting ground you are familiar with. The raid leader should know the raid area like the back of their hand. They should be familiar with the types of creatures<br>
present and their attack capabilities.<br>
<br>
- Clearly define the goals of the raid before embarking on the raid. One of the goals to consider is whether this is an experience making raid. Another is item acquisition.<br>
<br>
- Carefully consider the levels of participants. Even with a healer in their assigned group, it is inappropriate for a lvl 25 spellcaster to go into a situation where they would be facing lvl 35  mobs. <br>
<br>
- Carefully consider the makeup of groups in a raid. Is there an evac capable person in each group? Is there a healer in each group? A tank or other fighter capable of taunting a mob in each group? Don't be afraid to call off the raid if there is not a sufficient number of raiders to fill the jobs.<br>
<br>
- Designate authorized pullers after groups have been formed.<br>
<br>
- Designate one leader per group that reports problems and situations to the raid leader. <br>
<br>
- Plan for contingencies. What happens when player x goes linkdead? The objective is already camped, now what? Uber mob x spawns and threatens to wipe out the entire raiding party, what do you do? The raiding party is trained with everything from the dungeon, what's the command? Keep running scenarios through your mind and have a plan for what you would do for each.<br>
<br>
- Have a plan for post raid extraction. Teleporting out? Fighting back the way you came?<br>
<br>
- Have a plan for the worse case scenario... complete raiding party wipe out. Who will be retrieving the corpses? Who will be performing resurrections? Where is a safe location to drag corpses to should the dead player not be online anymore?<br>
<br>
- Designate a second in command for the raid. This person should also be familiar with the goals and location of the raid. If the leader is knocked out of action (linkdead), then it is this person's responsibility to assume leadership of the raid until the raid leader returns.<br>
<br>
- Post raid analysis. Were the objectives of the raid met? Did anyone die? If so, why? Was corpse recovery performed in a timely manner? Did everyone have fun?<br>
<br>
There are a number of other things that make for a successful raid, but these are the basics.<br>
<br>
I propose that from here on out, every raid is prefaced with a detailed plan here on the message boards. Location (both gathering and raid), time, objective(s), level requirements, class requirements. Include a link to an online map of the raid location so that participants can become more familiar with the raid location. Talk about mobs that will be encountered and what their methods of attack could be.<br>
<br>
As always, comment and suggestions are welcome <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
