<br>
In all your example's you make the leader of a particular event solely responsible for the total outcome of said event from start to finish, but you leave out the important fact that there is more than just a leader on a raid. All participants in a raid have a huge effect on the outcome (from the very start of meeting up, to the very end of everyone leaving). If the group or groups dont stick to the plan then anything can happen no matter what the leader is trying to do. In your message, you make it sound that every moment of the raid was a problem and how can that be so. <br>
<br>
I have some issues with the event on Friday night and post event analysis to provide, but this is the first moment I have had to sit down and type it up so here it is.<br>
<br>
1) First and foremost, I would like to thank all the wolves that attended this event, we had a very challenging and lengthy camp, 12 or so wolves were the total count of participants. Overall, it was a good event and good exp was had by all, but at the very end some 5 hours later, when the group dwindled down to about 7 or so we had a night mare problem that occurred. At the very end the ones who stayed for the long haul ended up hauling out their corpses in a most painful corpse retrieval.<br>
<br>
2) The meet, well we started-off on time but very few would meet in Freeport (which was in the event instructions) for a common tele, so we had to change the meeting spot on the fly and meet up at the druid ring near guk. Just meeting at guk would have worked but there was a chance that we would not go to guk first so a common meeting point was the original idea. So with a little delay we all ended up outside guk. So far the event at this point is going well and the meeting delay is normal for this number of participants.<br>
<br>
3) I asked if there were items in guk that anyone wanted, and a few items were asked for and we made arrangements to look for the items. At this point event still going fine.<br>
<br>
4) Foodang lead the group down to Lguk and to the jail room, Foodang was most familur with layout of guk so he was tasked with leading us near our first camp which was the Froglok noble. It was a little difficult keeping the group together because sometimes participants went wandering around on there own and did not stick together. Eventually we made it to the jail room with all 12. We held this position easily with this number and all was well. We pulled as much as the group wanted and the mid levels (30 ish level) group were getting great exp from all the reds they were getting the kills for. And the upper group was getting plenty of blue stuff. All was well here at this point too.<br>
<br>
5) People start to leave.... now this is understandable when you dig into a camp (several hours) that starts to drag out while you wait for a particular mob to spawn. Now we need to keep in mind we are not on a plane run but camping lower guk. At this point our group went from 12 or so wolves (6 mid level and 6 high level) to 6 or 7  and of that number only a couple high level. This is where the situation starts to easily go beyond any leaders ability to control. You cannot force the evacers or res'ers or high level peeps to stay, if they want to go they are free to go. So you ask the hard core if they want to stay and if they all say yes then you stay, and I will remind everyone that all wanted to stay even though everyone knew it was very risky to stay.<br>
<br>
6) I asked the wolves that are left if they wanted to stay and continue to camp the jail, and the answer is yes, nobody was forced to stay but all wanted to stay because the exp was great and the camp was still going smothly. So we continue to camp jail with out any problem, we pull a steady stream of high level mobs and all goes well until a bad decision was made and more than one person started pulling.<br>
<br>
7) One moment everything was great….. and in a flash suddenly I realize one of the group had gone off wandering around alone, I franticly tell them not to do this, but in seconds they got jumped by mobs and quickly are being killed as they run back to us with the mobs in tow. When pulling to a camp you balance the power of the group against the speed/threat of the pulls and you factor in adds and all goes well. But when someone goes off and runs around a dangerous place, and brings a train back near the group, well things begin to happen fast. And of course its so late in the evening we do not have the luxury of evacer. And even if we did have evac everyone kept fighting because we had a chance to win, or so all thought because some did not know we had lost one to the train and in a small group losing one can and did lead to losing all.<br>
<br>
8) So we all die, and die and die, die die die!!!!!!! At this late hour (3ish AM cst) deep in guk there are not many there still and only one cleric I could find and the cleric did not want to help at all (. So we spent almost 2 hours trying to get 49 res's and get out of guk. And so for the ones that stayed till the bitter end I can understand them not liking that part.<br>
<br>
I was the leader of that event and yes I am disappointed that in the end it got very tough and went sour (and a specific reason why it went sour), but that is no reason to make like the whole event was a waste. The event lasted a long time and the first mob we were camping for never showed and that was just bad luck. The wolves that were left at the end wanted to be there and knew what it was like and could have left at any time. If everyone will go back and read my post I was very clear on exactly what this event was about and who should go. Of the ones that stayed till the end I would like to thank all who helped get everyone to a zone or the corpse to the zone.<br>
<br>
With all that said, the event went ok but could have been improved easily and next time it will go smother. <br>
<br>
And yes I am planning another event and this one will be a different style and more focused on one or two goals and can be completed in 3 hours or less. I will try to avoid the pitfalls of this last one but anyone that has been on dangerous raids know the risks, sometimes its glory and you will be praised and other times it will not be so good and you will be criticized but hind sight is always 20/20.<br>
<br>
I don’t want anyone that is considering starting an event but will not because they are afraid it will not go well and they might get post event criticism to just not plan one, you got to get out there and play the game, take the risks and hope for glory.<br>
<br>
Again I would like to thank all who showed up and hope you will show up on the next one as well, I had many tells from wolves that they enjoyed themselves greatly even at the bitter end. <br>
<br>
P.S. just a little hint on the next event, it will be in the next couple of weeks and will involve killing one level 54 zombie with high hit points. Spawn time fast, and kill time fast if we can get the same number of participants. More information to come.<br>
<br>
Molotov ShadowStorm<br>
Aegis Wolves Elder<br>
49th Season Shadow Knight  <br>
