<br>
But It sounds to me like it was a blast.  But then I like unexpected bumps it's the boring monotony of camping that kills me.  Of course thought the longest corpse recovery I was on was 2 hours in OOT.  <br>
<br>
Just some two cents about planning though<br>
<br>
I have to agree with Larou here a few things need to be there but niccolo macheiavelli(sp) is not needed.<br>
<br>
1) &quot;The possible risks&quot; known should be put out(not things like group death, Members go LD or trains, we're EQ players thats part of life). Thinks like level of zone, Quality of zone players, Evac or rez possible, level caps or familiarity with the area.  From these basic things a player should be able to determine if they want to go.<br>
<br>
2) &quot;Objective and basic plan&quot;.  Kill Mob, Meet here at time then go to here to kill it.  Yes this basic.<br>
<br>
3) &quot;back up or fall back spot&quot;.  This does not mean evac or rezzer those are nice when there avialible but be adaptable have a basic fall back point if &quot;fall back&quot; is yelled run to X zone or X safe place to die, again simple. Make sure every one knows the way.  But as larou says it's an adventure game were here for risks.  But keep in mind where a big guild if some one where really stuck They have 8hrs to one week if off line we can arrange for something.  Also the guild does have back up mules for the worst case scenario, which I think would be hard to make happen in this guild.<br>
<br>
4) &quot;Who gives the orders&quot;. Only one person should tell the group/groups when to attack and when to fall back.  There should be one fall back person in case the other dies first or goes LD.  If the leader misses a call because something unexpected happened well thats what happens when unexpected things happen, things don't always go like clock work.  This game is designed to prevent you from getting exp other wise it wouldn't be a challenge.<br>
<br>
5) &quot;Who does the pulling&quot;. I can only tell you how devestaded a group can be by multiple pullers.  If your going to have multiple pullers they should take ques from the leader and they should have some basic hot keys Ditch it, bring it, forget it.<br>
<br>
<br>
I think any thing more than those five basic thinngs is to much. it should always be broken down afterwards  for all to see so we can learn from past successes and victories. <br>
<br>
<br>
One thing I know from stratagy games and the army Keep the plans very simple.  <br>
A) Not every one is stratigic minded and they need to be able to follow the plan<br>
B) Every plan of battle no matter how well thought out is only good until first contact with the enemy. Most the best successes in history where accidents or plans followed to closely not allowing for adaptability.  Battle of Cow pens, Battle of the buiscuts, Midway, Falkirk, Loren, Hastings,  invasion of crete and the sacking of Rome etc.... <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Also I don't beleive the leader is completely responsibe for the group in EQ.  this is not the Army you can't shoot people for disobaying orders or even issue orders for that matter.  I dare you to tell your only Rezzer what their &quot;going&quot; to do.  You can ask and if they do it cool. The leader is not soully responsible for everything where all in this together and if we don't work togther well die together.  If people misunderstand something don't listen to what others say or just unexpected things happen like members going LD amidst a fight or a train being dragged through your fight can be held on their head (some typical situations there are others).  Yes they are required to react and that is all that can be expected of them. However in EQ a train comming through can pretty much mean grab a /loc because there may not be any reacting.  <br>
<br>
My thoughts <br>
<br>
