<br>
It is unreasonable to expect a cleric to break camp to do a res.  Presumably he was with four or five other people who were his primary responsibility.  On the other hand, it is unconscionable to res someone unprotected into a hot zone without extreme extenuating circumstances.  If I am grouped, it is always my policy that if you want a res, you bring the body to me.  On the other hand, if I don't feel I can do the res safely, I simply won't do it. I have made more than one person unhappy because of that, but let's face it.  No one is entitled to a res.  I wasn't there, but as it has been described to me, the res's should never have been done.  If I am doing a res in a dungeon, you can bet I have party approval and a tacit agreement from them to protect during the res.  This also means that I have confidence in my group's ability to hold the room long enough to get the job done.  If the cleric and his group were run out of the room, then things happen.  If they decided to move after the res and before Foo had zoned back in, they should all be shot.  You can call this unamed cleric a bonehead for improperly res'ing into a hot zone, and I'll stand beside you and cheer you on.  But don't expect a cleric to break camp to come res you.  If it happens, all the more wonderful.<br>
<br>
